---
import SiteLayout from "../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";

export const meta = {
  title: "Factor Calculator",
  description: "What are the hidden numbers making up your value? Discover all factors, prime factorization, and pairs instantly.",
  category: "tool",
  published: "2026-03-15",
};

const schema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@graph": [
    {
      "@type": "FAQPage",
      "mainEntity": [
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What are factors of a number?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Factors are integers that you can multiply together to get a specific original number. Alternatively, factors are numbers that divide into the original number exactly, leaving no remainder."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How do you find the prime factorization of a number?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Prime factorization involves repeatedly dividing a number by prime numbers (2, 3, 5, 7, etc.) until the only remaining factors are prime numbers. This breaks the number down into a product of exclusively prime numbers."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Can negative numbers have factors?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Yes, negative numbers have factors. The factors of a negative number are simply the factors of its absolute value, but typically factor pairs are considered where one number is positive and the other is negative (e.g., factors of -6 are -1, 1, -2, 2, -3, 3, -6, 6)."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Is 1 a factor of every number?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Yes, the number 1 is a universal factor. It divides exactly into every integer, meaning it is a factor of every number."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is the difference between factors and multiples?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "A factor is a number that divides exactly into another number (e.g., 5 is a factor of 20). A multiple is the result of multiplying a number by an integer (e.g., 20 is a multiple of 5)."
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "@type": "Article",
      "headline": meta.title,
      "description": meta.description,
      "author": {
        "@type": "Organization",
        "name": "SiliconBased"
      }
    }
  ]
};
---

<SiteLayout site="siliconbased" title={meta.title} description={meta.description} canonical="https://siliconbased.dev/factor-calculator" schema={schema}>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>Factor Calculator</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">Instantly find all factors, factor pairs, and the prime factorization of any integer.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="calculator-container">
      <div class="input-group">
        <label for="num-input">Enter a number (integer):</label>
        <div class="input-wrapper">
          <input type="number" id="num-input" placeholder="e.g. 100" min="1" step="1" />
        </div>
        <p class="error-msg" id="num-error" style="color: #ef4444; font-size: 0.85rem; margin-top: 0.5rem; display: none;"></p>
      </div>

      <div id="results-area" style="display: none;">
        <div class="result-card">
          <div class="calc-result-label">Total Factors</div>
          <div class="result-value" id="total-factors-val">-</div>
        </div>

        <div class="results-grid">
          <div class="result-box">
            <h3>All Factors</h3>
            <div id="all-factors-val" class="factor-list"></div>
          </div>

          <div class="result-box">
            <h3>Factor Pairs</h3>
            <div id="factor-pairs-val" class="factor-list"></div>
          </div>

          <div class="result-box" style="grid-column: 1 / -1;">
            <h3>Prime Factorization</h3>
            <div id="prime-factors-val" class="factor-list prime-list"></div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="explainer">
      <h2>How the Factor Calculator Works</h2>
      <p>
        The Factor Calculator is a tool designed to instantly break down any integer into its constituent building blocks.
        Whether you're a student checking your math homework, a programmer writing algorithms, or a professional doing data analysis,
        understanding the composition of numbers is a fundamental requirement.
      </p>

      <h3>What is a Factor?</h3>
      <p>
        In mathematics, a factor is an integer that can be multiplied by another integer to produce a specific number. Alternatively,
        you can think of factors as numbers that divide perfectly into a target number, leaving no remainder.
      </p>
      <p>
        For instance, if we consider the number <strong>12</strong>:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><code>1 &times; 12 = 12</code>, so 1 and 12 are factors.</li>
        <li><code>2 &times; 6 = 12</code>, so 2 and 6 are factors.</li>
        <li><code>3 &times; 4 = 12</code>, so 3 and 4 are factors.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Therefore, the complete list of factors for the number 12 is: <strong>1, 2, 3, 4, 6, 12</strong>.
      </p>

      <h3>Factor Pairs Explained</h3>
      <p>
        Factors typically come in pairs. A factor pair is simply a set of two integers that, when multiplied together, result in the original number.
        As shown in the example above, the factor pairs for 12 are (1, 12), (2, 6), and (3, 4).
      </p>
      <p>
        If a number is a perfect square, such as 25 or 36, one of its factor pairs will consist of the same number repeated (e.g., 5 &times; 5 = 25).
        In this case, the number has an odd number of unique factors, because the square root is only listed once in the final sequence.
      </p>

      <h3>What is Prime Factorization?</h3>
      <p>
        While identifying all factors gives you the complete list of divisors, <strong>prime factorization</strong> breaks a number down into its most fundamental prime components.
        A prime number is a number greater than 1 that has only two factors: 1 and itself (e.g., 2, 3, 5, 7, 11).
      </p>
      <p>
        The Fundamental Theorem of Arithmetic states that every integer greater than 1 either is a prime number itself or can be represented as a unique product of prime numbers.
        Our calculator employs a division algorithm to repeatedly extract prime factors from your input number.
      </p>
      <p>
        For example, the prime factorization of <strong>60</strong> is found by continuously dividing by the smallest possible prime numbers:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>60 &divide; 2 = 30</li>
        <li>30 &divide; 2 = 15</li>
        <li>15 &divide; 3 = 5</li>
        <li>5 &divide; 5 = 1 (we are done)</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Thus, the prime factorization of 60 is written as <strong>2 &times; 2 &times; 3 &times; 5</strong>, or in exponential form: <strong>2<sup>2</sup> &times; 3 &times; 5</strong>.
      </p>

      <h3>How to Use the Calculator</h3>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Enter your number:</strong> Type any positive integer into the input field. The calculator processes inputs in real-time.</li>
        <li><strong>View All Factors:</strong> The tool will instantly generate a comma-separated list of all numbers that divide evenly into your input.</li>
        <li><strong>Examine Factor Pairs:</strong> Review the groupings of two numbers that multiply to create your target value.</li>
        <li><strong>Analyze Prime Factors:</strong> See the number stripped down to its core prime building blocks, displayed as an equation.</li>
      </ol>
      <p>
        The underlying algorithm efficiently computes factors by iterating up to the square root of your number. This ensures fast, responsive calculations even for relatively large integers, all executed locally within your browser for immediate results.
      </p>

      <div class="highlight-box">
        <strong>Need to calculate volume for a project?</strong> Try our <a href="/cubic-yard-calculator">Cubic Yard Calculator</a> to figure out how much dirt, mulch, or concrete you need based on linear dimensions.
      </div>
    </div>

    <section class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <details>
        <summary>What are factors of a number?</summary>
        <p>Factors are integers that you can multiply together to get a specific original number. Alternatively, factors are numbers that divide into the original number exactly, leaving no remainder.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>How do you find the prime factorization of a number?</summary>
        <p>Prime factorization involves repeatedly dividing a number by prime numbers (2, 3, 5, 7, etc.) until the only remaining factors are prime numbers. This breaks the number down into a product of exclusively prime numbers.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>Can negative numbers have factors?</summary>
        <p>Yes, negative numbers have factors. The factors of a negative number are simply the factors of its absolute value, but typically factor pairs are considered where one number is positive and the other is negative (e.g., factors of -6 are -1, 1, -2, 2, -3, 3, -6, 6).</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>Is 1 a factor of every number?</summary>
        <p>Yes, the number 1 is a universal factor. It divides exactly into every integer, meaning it is a factor of every number.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>What is the difference between factors and multiples?</summary>
        <p>A factor is a number that divides exactly into another number (e.g., 5 is a factor of 20). A multiple is the result of multiplying a number by an integer (e.g., 20 is a multiple of 5).</p>
      </details>
    </section>
  </div>

  <script is:inline>
    document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
      const numInput = document.getElementById('num-input');
      const numError = document.getElementById('num-error');
      const resultsArea = document.getElementById('results-area');

      const totalFactorsVal = document.getElementById('total-factors-val');
      const allFactorsVal = document.getElementById('all-factors-val');
      const factorPairsVal = document.getElementById('factor-pairs-val');
      const primeFactorsVal = document.getElementById('prime-factors-val');

      function calculateFactors(n) {
        let factors = [];
        for (let i = 1; i <= Math.sqrt(n); i++) {
          if (n % i === 0) {
            factors.push(i);
            if (i !== n / i) {
              factors.push(n / i);
            }
          }
        }
        return factors.sort((a, b) => a - b);
      }

      function getFactorPairs(factors, n) {
        let pairs = [];
        for (let i = 0; i < factors.length; i++) {
          let a = factors[i];
          let b = n / a;
          if (a <= b) {
            pairs.push(`(${a}, ${b})`);
          }
        }
        return pairs;
      }

      function getPrimeFactorization(n) {
        if (n <= 1) return "None";
        let factors = [];
        let divisor = 2;

        while (n >= 2) {
          if (n % divisor === 0) {
            factors.push(divisor);
            n = n / divisor;
          } else {
            divisor++;
          }
        }

        // Group into powers
        let counts = {};
        factors.forEach(f => {
          counts[f] = (counts[f] || 0) + 1;
        });

        let expression = [];
        for (const [base, exp] of Object.entries(counts)) {
          if (exp > 1) {
            expression.push(`${base}<sup>${exp}</sup>`);
          } else {
            expression.push(base);
          }
        }
        return expression.join(' &times; ');
      }

      function handleInput() {
        const val = numInput.value;

        if (!val) {
          resultsArea.style.display = 'none';
          numError.style.display = 'none';
          numInput.style.borderColor = '';
          return;
        }

        const num = parseFloat(val);

        if (isNaN(num) || !Number.isInteger(num) || num <= 0) {
          resultsArea.style.display = 'none';
          numError.textContent = "Please enter a positive integer greater than 0.";
          numError.style.display = 'block';
          numInput.style.borderColor = '#ef4444';
          return;
        }

        // Valid input
        numError.style.display = 'none';
        numInput.style.borderColor = '';

        // Calculate
        const factors = calculateFactors(num);
        const pairs = getFactorPairs(factors, num);
        const primeFact = getPrimeFactorization(num);

        // Update UI
        totalFactorsVal.textContent = factors.length;
        allFactorsVal.innerHTML = factors.join(', ');
        factorPairsVal.innerHTML = pairs.join('<br>');
        primeFactorsVal.innerHTML = primeFact;

        resultsArea.style.display = 'block';
      }

      numInput.addEventListener('input', handleInput);
    });
  </script>

  <style is:inline>
    .results-grid {
      display: grid;
      grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr;
      gap: 1.5rem;
      margin-top: 1.5rem;
    }
    .result-box {
      background: var(--bg-color);
      border: 1px solid var(--border-color);
      border-radius: 8px;
      padding: 1.5rem;
    }
    .result-box h3 {
      margin-top: 0;
      margin-bottom: 1rem;
      font-size: 1.1rem;
      color: var(--text-primary);
    }
    .factor-list {
      font-family: var(--font-mono);
      color: var(--text-secondary);
      line-height: 1.8;
      word-break: break-all;
    }
    .prime-list {
      font-size: 1.2rem;
      color: var(--accent-color);
      font-weight: 600;
    }
    @media (max-width: 640px) {
      .results-grid {
        grid-template-columns: 1fr;
      }
    }
    .page-content { max-width: 900px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 2rem 1.5rem; }
    .hero { text-align: center; padding: 3rem 0 2rem; }
    .hero h1 { font-size: 2.2rem; font-weight: 800; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }
    .subtitle { color: var(--text-secondary); font-size: 1.1rem; }
    .calculator-container { background: var(--card-bg); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 12px; padding: 2rem; margin: 2rem 0; }
    input, select { background: var(--bg-color); color: var(--text-primary); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); padding: 0.75rem 1rem; border-radius: 8px; width: 100%; font-size: 1rem; }
    input:focus, select:focus { outline: none; border-color: var(--accent-color); box-shadow: 0 0 0 3px color-mix(in srgb, var(--accent-color) 20%, transparent); }
    button { background: var(--accent-color); color: white; border: none; padding: 0.75rem 2rem; border-radius: 8px; font-weight: 600; cursor: pointer; font-size: 1rem; }
    button:hover { opacity: 0.9; }
    .result-card { background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--accent-color) 10%, transparent); border: 1px solid var(--accent-color); border-radius: 12px; padding: 1.5rem; margin: 1.5rem 0; text-align: center; }
    .result-value { font-size: 2.5rem; font-weight: 800; color: var(--accent-color); }
    .faq-section details { margin: 1rem 0; padding: 1rem; background: var(--card-bg); border-radius: 8px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); }
    .faq-section summary { font-weight: 600; cursor: pointer; }
  </style>
</SiteLayout>
